column1: #Text=Ninot le Petit ( also Johannes Parvi ) ( fl. ca. 1500 – 1520 ) was a French composer of the Renaissance , probably associated with the French royal chapel .
#Text=Although a substantial amount of his music has survived in several sources , his actual name is not known with certainty .
#Text=Two identifications have been proposed by musicologists in the latter half of the 20th century .

#Text=The first possibility , suggested by Barton Hudson in 1979 , is that le Petit may have been Johannes Baltazar alias le Petit , since a singer of that name was in the papal chapel between 1488 and 1502 , and his name resembles that in the attribution of some " le Petit " motets in a Vatican manuscript .

column1: #Text=The second possibility is that " le Petit " may be the same as Jean Lepetit , the singing master at Langres Cathedral between 1506 and 1510 .
#Text=Baltazar died in 1502 , Lepetit after 1529 ; stylistically the music of le Petit suggests composition in the first two decades of the 16th century .
#Text=Le Petit 's style is similar to that of Antoine de Févin and Jean Mouton , the two most famous French composers associated with the French royal chapel .
#Text=He preferred clear harmonies , a texture occasionally broken by long duets , and contrasting sections in triple meter , somewhat blending the styles of Févin and Mouton .
#Text=The chansons are light and open in texture , foreshadowing the developments in the genre later in the century .

#Text=Le Petit was listed by Pierre Moulu in his famous motet Mater floreat florescat as one of the leading composers of the day ( this work , probably written around 1517 , provides to musicologists a particularly useful list of composers working at the time , naming the composers associated with the French royal chapel which Moulu thought the most eloquent of the time ) .
#Text=One mass by le Petit has survived , as well as four motets and 16 chansons .

#Text=Many of his works have also been attributed to others ; some , such as Lourdault lourdault garde que tu feras , are now considered to be reliably the work of others ( in that case , Loyset Compère ) .

#Text=Since one large block of chansons survived in one manuscript , but relatively little sacred music , and yet Moulu listed him as a famous composer , it can be inferred that most of his music has been lost .
#Text=Missa sine nomine ( mass without a name )
#Text=Si oblitus fuero tui ( has also been attributed to Jacob Obrecht )
#Text=Many of these are lacking a bass voice part , since the bass part-book has been lost from the manuscript .
